    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-28T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-28T20:00:00-05:00" n="674"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d674">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">394.115 Panay/211: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-29T10:00:00+09:00"
                            >December 29, 1937—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 29—2:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>694. Department’s 381, December 28, 5 p.m.<note n="2" xml:id="d674fn2">Not
                        printed; see Department’s telegram No. 361, December 18, 6 p.m., <ref
                            target="frus1931-41v01#pg_530">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 530</ref>.</note> I immediately
                    consulted Prince Tokugawa<note n="3" xml:id="d674fn3">President of the Japanese
                        House of Peers and of the America-Japan Society.</note> with regard to the
                    disposal of donations received in connection with the <hi rend="italic"
                        >Panay</hi> incident and am in constant touch with the officers of the
                    America-Japan Society who have agreed to handle the matter and are now
                    discussing the most helpful way to use the funds in the interests of
                    Japanese-American friendship. They now have under consideration the possible
                    endowment of a hospital bed but it is difficult to reach a decision until the
                    final approximate amount of contributed money can be ascertained. I have urged
                    the <pb facs="0528" n="520" xml:id="pg_520"/> importance of an early decision as
                    well as a public statement by Prince Tokugawa as soon as the plans can be
                    settled.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
